Example of auth.json
--------------------
1️⃣ Step 1 — Login Script (Create auth.json)
First we login one time and save the login session.
login.py
--------
# login.py

    from playwright.sync_api import sync_playwright

    with sync_playwright() as p:

        browser = p.chromium.launch(headless=False)

        context = browser.new_context()

        page = context.new_page()

        # Open login page
        page.goto("https://example.com/login")

        # Enter credentials
        page.fill("#username", "testuser")
        page.fill("#password", "password123")

        # Click login
        page.click("#login")

        # Save login session
        context.storage_state(path="auth.json")

        browser.close()

2️⃣ What Happens When This Script Runs
Execution flow:
    Open Browser
        ↓
    Go to Login Page
        ↓
    Enter Username & Password
        ↓
    Login Successful
        ↓
    Playwright saves login session
        ↓
    auth.json file is created

Now your project folder will look like:
    project/
    │
    ├── login.py
    ├── auth.json
    ├── conftest.py
    └── test_dashboard.py

3️⃣ What Is Inside auth.json
auth.json stores login session data , not credentials.
Example:
    {
        "cookies": [
            {
            "name": "session_id",
            "value": "abc123"
            }
        ],
        "origins": []
    }

This means:
    User session is saved
So the website knows the user is already logged in.

4️⃣ Step 2 — Use auth.json in Tests
Now we load this login session.
conftest.py
-----------
    import pytest
    from playwright.sync_api import sync_playwright

    @pytest.fixture(scope="session")
    def browser_context():

        with sync_playwright() as p:

            browser = p.chromium.launch()

            context = browser.new_context(storage_state="auth.json")

            yield context

            browser.close()
Explanation:
------------
    Start browser
        ↓
    Load auth.json
        ↓
    User already logged in

